  modelAnswer:
    "The eval team is about to lose a fight it should win, because 'quality has a price' is a slogan and finance brought a spreadsheet. The honest embarrassment: the program preaching measurement discipline (016 through 045) never measured itself. It grew by accretion — every incident minted a permanent suite at maximum frequency, nothing was ever tiered or retired — and accretion without portfolio review is how insurance becomes hoarding. 038's diagnosis applies verbatim, one level up: an undifferentiated bill, blamed on 'the model' then, defended with 'quality' now, and in both cases the fix is the same — instrument where the money goes, then cut by evidence.\n\nBuild the yield curve: cost per suite per run, catch-rate per dollar. Then tier ruthlessly and honestly. Change-risk tiering for the gates: 045's suite keeps full teeth for behavior-class changes and drops to smoke for typo-tier diffs — the gate's legitimacy (024) depends on it being fast and proportionate, and running everything on everything is how gates get bypassed anyway. Sampling for volume: production monitoring returns to its 016 roots — stratified samples with drift-triggered escalation, not the full-coverage judge-call habit the automation quietly grew into. Caching for redundancy: unchanged behavior plus unchanged judge version is a replayable verdict, not a new bill. And retirement with 064's honors for suites whose failure class is architecturally dead — the 044 attacks that 040's identity intersection made structurally impossible deserve an archive, not a nightly run.\n\nThen the finance meeting, in their language: measurement is insurance, and insurance gets priced by the risk it retires. Present the tier structure as a premium schedule — this layer insures against 015-class incidents (annual cost X, incident cost 30X), this one against silent regressions (045's history of catches attached). Make finance co-author of the tiers (054's mechanism: their veto becomes their signature). The number that wins: spend down 40%, gate coverage on every risk class that has EVER fired — unchanged. And hold the falsifier without flinching: if the instrumentation shows the big lines are irreducible and productive, then the program is honestly expensive, and the real conversation is what risk tolerance the customer is buying — which is finance's call to make with open eyes, not the eval team's to make by slogan.",
