  modelAnswer:
    "Concede the physics first: the reviewers didn't fail the gate — the gate's design failed them, on schedule. When automation is right 99% of the time, sustained human vigilance is not a discipline problem, it's a documented impossibility (automation bias is what reliable systems DO to their overseers), and 'review everything uniformly forever' is a design that guarantees 4-second clicks while manufacturing a paper trail that says diligence. The audit committee's question is exactly right, and the answer must be a redesign, because the honest current answer is: oversight here means legal cover that won't survive its first test.\n\nRedesign around attention as the scarce input. Triage: risk-score the queue — amount, vendor novelty, deviation-from-precedent, agent confidence — and let the routine 80% flow to SAMPLED review while human attention concentrates on the reviewable 20% (this is 010's earn-autonomy logic applied inside the rung: the boring classes have earned it; the novel ones haven't). Fewer items, reviewed deeply, beats everything, reviewed nominally. Measure the review itself: seed known-bad drafts — canaries built from the error classes that matter (wrong-vendor, policy-violating, 044's adversarial repurposes) — and track catch rates per reviewer. This is the move that answers the committee: 'human oversight' stops meaning 'a click occurred' and starts meaning 'measured 94% catch rate on seeded risks.' Make the deep-review interface structurally un-stampable: diffs against precedent highlighted, risk flags named, attestation that engages the specific flags — friction proportional to stakes (the approve button's frictionlessness was a design choice too; it chose throughput).\n\nClose the loop humanely: catch rates feed back to reviewers as their own calibration (a personal Gnomon), and chronic misses route as capability gaps, not discipline cases — the person who cleared 200 items in 19 minutes was set up by a queue that made that possible and a metric that made it look like productivity. And run the falsifier honestly: seed the canaries BEFORE redesigning everything — if 4-second reviews catch the seeded errors (glaring failures, efficient pattern-matching), the gate was healthier than its telemetry looked, and what the committee needs is the canary system as permanent proof rather than a rebuilt queue. Either way, the standing answer to 'what does oversight mean' becomes measurable: catch rate on seeded risk, attention where risk lives — which is the only definition that survives both the audit and the incident.",
